Guided Exercise: Use OpenShift Templates
Deploy and update an application from a template that is stored in another project.
You learn how to:
1️⃣ Deploy an application from a template in another project
2️⃣ Deploy an application from a custom template
3️⃣ Update an application using template parameters
________________________________________
Step 1 — Start the Lab Environment
Command:
lab start packaged-templates
What this does
The lab command prepares the environment:
•	Starts the cluster
•	Creates required resources
•	Configures permissions
This ensures the exercise works correctly.
________________________________________
Step 2 — Login to OpenShift
Command:
oc login -u developer -p developer \
https://api.ocp4.example.com:6443
Explanation
Part	Meaning
oc	OpenShift CLI
login	authenticate to cluster
-u developer	username
-p developer	password
URL	API server address
After login, you can manage resources in the cluster.
________________________________________
Step 3 — Discover Available Templates
Templates are stored in the openshift namespace.
Command:
oc get templates -n openshift
Example output:
NAME                    DESCRIPTION
cakephp-mysql-example   Example PHP app
mysql-persistent        MySQL database template
postgresql-ephemeral    PostgreSQL template
What this means
You are checking which templates are available in the cluster.
The template we want:
mysql-persistent
This template deploys a persistent MySQL database.
________________________________________
Step 4 — Inspect the Template
Command:
oc describe template mysql-persistent -n openshift
Purpose
Shows:
•	template description
•	parameters
•	objects created
Example objects:
Secret
Service
PersistentVolumeClaim
Deployment
Explanation
Resource	Purpose
Secret	store DB credentials
Service	expose database inside cluster
PVC	persistent storage
Deployment	runs MySQL container
So the template automatically deploys a complete database stack.
________________________________________
Step 5 — View Template Parameters
Command:
oc process --parameters mysql-persistent -n openshift
Example output:
MYSQL_USER
MYSQL_PASSWORD
MYSQL_DATABASE
VOLUME_CAPACITY
MYSQL_VERSION
Important
Some parameters are auto-generated.
Example:
MYSQL_PASSWORD  expression  [a-zA-Z0-9]{16}
Meaning:
OpenShift automatically generates a random password.
________________________________________
Step 6 — Create a New Project
Command:
oc new-project packaged-templates
What this does
Creates a namespace for your resources.
OpenShift projects = Kubernetes namespaces.
Now all resources will be created in:
packaged-templates
________________________________________
Step 7 — Deploy MySQL Using Template
Command:
oc new-app --template=mysql-persistent \
-p MYSQL_USER=user1 \
-p MYSQL_PASSWORD=mypasswd
Explanation
Part	Meaning
oc new-app	create application
--template	use template
-p	set parameter
Parameters used:
MYSQL_USER=user1
MYSQL_PASSWORD=mypasswd
OpenShift then creates:
secret/mysql
service/mysql
persistentvolumeclaim/mysql
deployment/mysql
________________________________________
Step 8 — Wait Until Pod Is Running
Command:
watch oc get pods
Example output:
NAME                     READY   STATUS
mysql-xxxx               1/1     Running
Explanation
Column	Meaning
READY	containers ready
STATUS	running state
1/1 Running means database is ready.
Stop watch:
Ctrl + C
________________________________________
Step 9 — Test Database Connection
Command:
oc run query-db -it --rm \
--image registry.ocp4.example.com:8443/rhel8/mysql-80 \
--restart Never --command -- \
/bin/bash -c \
"mysql -uuser1 -pmypasswd --protocol tcp \
-h mysql -P3306 sampledb -e 'SHOW DATABASES;'"
What this command does
Creates a temporary pod that connects to MySQL.
Options explanation:
Option	Meaning
oc run	create pod
-it	interactive
--rm	delete pod after execution
--image	container image
mysql command	execute database query
________________________________________
Query executed
SHOW DATABASES;
Output:
information_schema
performance_schema
sampledb
This confirms:
✔ MySQL is working
✔ Database is accessible
________________________________________
Step 10 — Deploy Custom Template
Custom template file:
roster-template.yaml
Command:
oc create -f roster-template.yaml
What this does
Creates a template resource in your project.
Important:
This does NOT deploy the app yet.
It only uploads the template.
________________________________________
Step 11 — Verify Template Exists
Command:
oc get templates
Output:
NAME
roster-template
________________________________________
Step 12 — Inspect Custom Template
Command:
oc describe template roster-template
Objects created:
Secret
Deployment
Service
Route
Explanation
Resource	Purpose
Secret	database credentials
Deployment	application container
Service	internal access
Route	external access
Routes are OpenShift-specific.
They expose applications to the internet.
________________________________________
Step 13 — View Template Parameters
Command:
oc process --parameters roster-template
Important parameters:
IMAGE
APPNAME
MYSQL_USER
MYSQL_PASSWORD
MYSQL_DATABASE
INIT_DB
INIT_DB parameter
True → initialize database
False → reuse existing data
________________________________________
Step 14 — Deploy Application from Template
Command:
oc process roster-template \
-p MYSQL_USER=user1 \
-p MYSQL_PASSWORD=mypasswd \
-p INIT_DB=true | oc apply -f -
Explanation
1️⃣ oc process generates manifests
2️⃣ pipe | sends output to next command
3️⃣ oc apply deploys resources
Resources created:
secret/mysql
deployment/do280-roster
service/do280-roster
route/do280-roster
________________________________________
Step 15 — Verify Pods
Command:
oc get pods
Example:
do280-roster-xxxx    Running
mysql-xxxx           Running
Now:
•	database running
•	application running
________________________________________
Step 16 — Get Application URL
Command:
oc get routes
Example output:
do280-roster-packaged-templates.apps.ocp4.example.com
Open in browser:
http://do280-roster-packaged-templates.apps.ocp4.example.com
You will see version 1 of the app.
________________________________________
Step 17 — Create Parameter File for Update
Create file:
roster-parameters.env
Content:
MYSQL_USER=user1
MYSQL_PASSWORD=mypasswd
IMAGE=registry.ocp4.example.com:8443/redhattraining/do280-roster:v2
Why parameter files?
Advantages:
✔ easier updates
✔ version control
✔ cleaner commands
________________________________________
Step 18 — Preview Changes
Command:
oc process roster-template \
--param-file=roster-parameters.env | oc diff -f -
Example output:
image: do280-roster:v1
→ image: do280-roster:v2
Also:
INIT_DB true → False
Meaning:
Database will not be reinitialized.
________________________________________
Step 19 — Apply Update
Command:
oc process roster-template \
--param-file=roster-parameters.env | oc apply -f -
Output:
deployment configured
service unchanged
route unchanged
Only the deployment changes.
________________________________________
Step 20 — Wait for New Pod
Command:
watch oc get pods
Example:
do280-roster-newpod Running
mysql Running
The application pod restarts with new image.
________________________________________
Step 21 — Verify Update
Refresh the web page.
You will see:
Version 2
Important:
✔ Database data still exists
✔ Only application updated
________________________________________
Step 22 — Finish Lab
Command:
lab finish packaged-templates
What it does
•	deletes resources
•	resets environment
•	prepares next lab
________________________________________
Full Workflow Summary
1. Login
oc login
2. View templates
oc get templates -n openshift
3. Deploy template
oc new-app --template
4. Verify pods
oc get pods
5. Process template
oc process TEMPLATE
6. Deploy resources
oc apply -f -
7. Update app
oc process --param-file | oc apply -f -
